WEBVTT

00:13.263 --> 00:15.891
<i>Once upon a time, a specific time,</i>

00:16.767 --> 00:23.023
<i>July 5th, 1825 to be exact,
52 men and women sailed out of Norway</i>

00:23.023 --> 00:25.859
<i>in an undersized sloop
they named</i> Restauration<i>.</i>

00:28.862 --> 00:31.865
<i>These immigrants
sought religious freedom from persecution,</i>

00:31.865 --> 00:33.534
<i>so they fled to America.</i>

00:35.994 --> 00:40.499
<i>Not just an improbable crossing,
an impossible one.</i>

00:44.837 --> 00:46.672
<i>How in the world did they make it?</i>

00:51.969 --> 00:53.595
<i>They had help, that's how.</i>

00:57.891 --> 00:59.643
<i>Tell me your journey, each of you.</i>

01:00.686 --> 01:04.147
<i>Tell me your life's voyage,
and I will tell you who you are.</i>

01:16.577 --> 01:20.914
<i>This fairy tale begins in a library
in Queens.</i>

01:26.420 --> 01:30.257
Hello! Hello!

01:31.967 --> 01:33.594
I am in distress!

01:34.678 --> 01:35.846
This is dire!

01:37.514 --> 01:39.349
I am in need of a toilet!

01:39.349 --> 01:42.895
Listen to my voice. Can you hear me?

01:43.437 --> 01:45.731
I got ears, don't I? Look.

01:45.731 --> 01:49.067
Well, you see I have ears too,
so why are you yelling?

01:49.943 --> 01:53.405
I need a piece of ID
before I give you the bathroom key.

01:53.405 --> 01:55.324
I don't have ID.

01:57.326 --> 01:58.785
Leave your bags here with me.

01:59.703 --> 02:01.580
These contain state secrets!

02:02.497 --> 02:03.498
Okay.

02:26.980 --> 02:27.981
Thank you, ma'am.

02:28.732 --> 02:29.733
My pleasure.

02:51.964 --> 02:54.091
- Hi.
- Do you need something?

02:54.091 --> 02:55.467
I was gonna help you with him.

02:59.054 --> 03:01.974
- Seems like you got that all figured out.
- Imagine that.

03:05.477 --> 03:06.854
Apollo.

03:06.854 --> 03:08.021
As in Creed?

03:08.605 --> 03:09.898
Actually, yeah, kinda.

03:15.612 --> 03:19.366
Do you wanna go, like--
Do you wanna go to dinner with me?

03:25.205 --> 03:26.832
- Please.
- No.

03:27.541 --> 03:31.211
<i>If Emma Valentine thought
Apollo Kagwa would give up this easily,</i>

03:31.211 --> 03:32.379
<i>she was mistaken.</i>

03:34.298 --> 03:38.051
<i>But to understand why and how
in the world, we must first go back.</i>

03:40.804 --> 03:41.889
<i>Way back.</i>

03:46.059 --> 03:49.062
<i>It was during
the great garbage strike of 1968</i>

03:49.563 --> 03:51.690
<i>that Brian West met Lillian Kagwa.</i>

03:59.656 --> 04:00.657
How are ya?

04:01.658 --> 04:04.286
I'm here to see a Mr. Pavel Arsenyev.

04:07.247 --> 04:09.333
Mr. Arsenyev, there's a...

04:09.333 --> 04:12.503
It's Brian West. Brian West.

04:12.503 --> 04:13.921
Brian West here to see you.

04:13.921 --> 04:15.839
<i>Fuck, fuck, fuck.</i>

04:19.009 --> 04:20.010
He'll be right out.

04:21.428 --> 04:22.429
Thank you.

04:25.516 --> 04:26.850
I'm his parole officer.

04:28.060 --> 04:32.898
I'm not supposed to tell you that though,
so you gotta keep that between us, right?

04:44.493 --> 04:47.538
- Kwagwa, that's an interesting name.
- Kagwa.

04:48.914 --> 04:50.874
Kwagwa. Kwaga.

04:52.918 --> 04:54.711
I don't date white men.

04:58.590 --> 04:59.591
Me neither.

05:03.095 --> 05:05.430
Hey, Kragwa. Kragwa.

05:05.430 --> 05:09.226
Lillian. Listen,

05:09.226 --> 05:13.814
a lot more monitoring needs to be done
around here, so I'll be back, all right?

05:14.523 --> 05:15.524
I'll see you later.

05:21.154 --> 05:24.491
Hey. That man is bad for business,

05:24.491 --> 05:29.204
and since he's so smitten with you,
that makes you bad for business, so...

05:29.705 --> 05:31.707
No, Mr. Arsenyev, I need this job.

05:31.707 --> 05:34.042
I don't want to hear it. Go.
Get your stuff.

05:40.382 --> 05:41.675
Hey, look who it is.

05:42.509 --> 05:46.847
Modeling agency/money laundering racket.
Not smart, Pavel. Not pretty.

05:47.431 --> 05:50.726
Not pretty at all. Back to jail for you.

06:00.319 --> 06:06.283
You got me fired. New job pays half.
New apartment only has one room.

06:07.075 --> 06:09.077
I liked it at the modeling agency.

06:12.706 --> 06:14.291
Just give me a chance.

06:14.958 --> 06:15.959
Never.

06:22.382 --> 06:24.384
<i>And he couldn't stay away.</i>

06:36.855 --> 06:37.689
Yes.

06:38.273 --> 06:40.817
<i>And that there is how Brian met Lillian,</i>

06:40.817 --> 06:43.487
<i>but didn't go on a real date
until years later.</i>

06:45.280 --> 06:47.616
You know, there's this place
right around the corner.

06:47.616 --> 06:49.493
It's really good. They have great--

06:49.493 --> 06:51.870
That's nice, but no.

06:52.621 --> 06:54.540
<i>Some may call that stalking.</i>

06:55.290 --> 06:57.501
<i>Apollo called it persistence.</i>

06:58.794 --> 07:01.547
Personally, I enjoy the simple things
like a stroll through the park

07:01.547 --> 07:03.131
- or something at the be--
- No.

07:06.301 --> 07:08.846
- Hey. Do you maybe just wanna go to--
- No.

07:24.361 --> 07:25.404
Yes.

07:30.492 --> 07:32.911
Re-- Great.

07:33.620 --> 07:34.705
Yeah.

07:36.874 --> 07:38.834
- Boones Mill?
- Yeah.

07:38.834 --> 07:42.087
Yeah, you haven't heard of it.
Population, 285.

07:44.965 --> 07:47.259
It's just where my parents landed,
I guess.

07:47.259 --> 07:49.136
Well, I bet your parents
have a lot of cool stories

07:49.136 --> 07:52.055
- about Boones fucking Mill.
- I've never spoken to them.

07:53.223 --> 07:55.893
No, I mean,
I'm sure I have actually spoken to them.

07:55.893 --> 08:00.230
I just don't remember the conversation
because they died when I was five.

08:00.814 --> 08:02.733
- I'm s--
- Don't-- Yeah. It's not a thing.

08:05.652 --> 08:07.070
So, how'd they die?

08:07.905 --> 08:08.906
Unimportant.

08:09.615 --> 08:10.616
Well, what happened?

08:10.616 --> 08:11.909
- To them?
- To you.

08:12.618 --> 08:15.204
Well, my sister Kim adopted me.
She's 13 years older.

08:15.204 --> 08:16.288
Shit.

08:16.288 --> 08:20.375
And Ms. Rook, the local librarian.
She would look after me when Kim couldn't.

08:20.375 --> 08:24.796
And she would let me and my best friend,
Michelle, watch all the movies.

08:25.380 --> 08:29.218
One day, I was 12,
and I picked up this movie at random--

08:29.218 --> 08:32.179
Well, random, it was the only movie
in the entire library

08:32.179 --> 08:34.181
that had Black people on the cover.

08:34.181 --> 08:35.432
- <i>Quilombo</i>.
- Okay.

08:35.432 --> 08:37.558
It's about the uprisings in Brazil,
and it's just like

08:37.558 --> 08:40.270
a ton of Portuguese people
just getting, like...

08:40.895 --> 08:43.982
brutally killed by slaves.

08:47.236 --> 08:48.237
That's fucking awesome.

08:48.237 --> 08:51.240
Yeah, actually, it was watching that movie
that made me--

08:52.449 --> 08:53.450
- What?
- Oh, my God.

08:53.450 --> 08:55.077
Do you know that I just realized
right this second

08:55.077 --> 08:57.246
that movies are called movies
because they move.

08:58.872 --> 09:00.082
Movies!

09:01.333 --> 09:03.043
I haven't thought about that one.
It's true.

09:03.043 --> 09:04.878
- Wow.
- Well, they do move.

09:10.884 --> 09:16.557
Anyhoo. <i>Quilombo</i> made me realize
how big the world was.

09:17.057 --> 09:21.436
Bigger than Boones fucking Mill.
And I wanted to see it. All of it.

09:27.484 --> 09:28.944
What about your peeps?

09:34.116 --> 09:36.910
One sad story's enough for the first date.

09:42.291 --> 09:44.710
Wow.
One of your eyes is bigger than the other.

09:45.419 --> 09:46.420
- God.
- What?

09:46.420 --> 09:48.797
That's not a bad thing.
That's a beautiful thing.

09:48.797 --> 09:50.716
I think it's gorgeous, frankly.

09:50.716 --> 09:53.343
You're the most gorgeous person
I've ever seen.

09:53.844 --> 09:55.929
Ever known. I mean, your soul is--

09:55.929 --> 09:57.264
- My soul?
- Yeah.

09:57.264 --> 09:58.348
Dude, no.

09:58.348 --> 10:00.100
- I mean, think of the kids we'd have.
- Kids?

10:00.100 --> 10:02.186
- I never cared if I had a boy, a girl...
- Okay.

10:02.186 --> 10:07.733
- ...twins, triplets, quadruplet--
- Okay. Apollo. Stop. Seriously.

10:08.442 --> 10:10.944
What? I mean,
some people wanna be an astronaut,

10:10.944 --> 10:14.740
some people wanna be a scientist,
some people wanna be a zookeeper.

10:14.740 --> 10:17.492
- A zookeeper? That's pretty cool.
- I just wanna be a good father

10:18.076 --> 10:19.453
to the kid I end up having.

10:23.165 --> 10:26.627
No, don't do that. Don't do that look.
Do a different look.

10:30.088 --> 10:34.551
The reason I said no to you
when you first asked me out--

10:34.551 --> 10:36.094
And the six times after that.

10:37.221 --> 10:39.056
And the six times after that

10:40.724 --> 10:44.394
is because I'm moving to Brazil,
and I don't know for how long.

10:46.813 --> 10:47.814
That can't be.

10:48.398 --> 10:49.858
And yet, it does be.

10:51.860 --> 10:54.238
No. No. I'm the god Apollo.

10:54.238 --> 10:55.322
Excuse me?

10:57.991 --> 10:59.910
- I am the god Apollo...
- God.

10:59.910 --> 11:02.412
...and I command you to stay.

11:38.323 --> 11:40.200
<i>This is the final boarding call,</i>

11:40.200 --> 11:45.455
- <i>flight 613 to São Paulo at Gate 530.</i>
- Goodbye.

11:45.956 --> 11:49.459
<i>Final boarding call
for flight 613 to São Paulo.</i>

11:49.960 --> 11:54.548
<i>All ticketed passengers,
please board now at Gate 530.</i>

12:04.308 --> 12:05.475
Sake?

12:05.475 --> 12:07.644
I don't drink, but--

12:08.145 --> 12:09.479
Idiots don't drink.

12:09.980 --> 12:11.064
You don't drink?

12:11.064 --> 12:12.149
Yeah. Idiot.

12:13.150 --> 12:14.151
Thank you.

12:15.944 --> 12:17.613
So, tell me something else.

12:17.613 --> 12:19.072
What should I tell ya?

12:20.157 --> 12:22.659
Well, you can't know anything
until you know everything,

12:22.659 --> 12:24.828
so everything it is.

12:24.828 --> 12:26.538
Everything it is--

12:28.332 --> 12:29.875
<i>Well, I was born in Syracuse.</i>

12:30.459 --> 12:32.836
<i>My family moved down here,
so I was raised in the city.</i>

12:33.962 --> 12:35.506
<i>I spent a lot of time in the theater.</i>

12:36.089 --> 12:40.177
<i>I used to love watching the pictures,
you know, I'd sell my little candy,</i>

12:40.177 --> 12:41.345
<i>try and make some money.</i>

12:42.554 --> 12:44.431
<i>I grew up fast. You know, New York, it...</i>

12:44.431 --> 12:46.183
- Thank you.
- <i>...it'll do that to you.</i>

12:52.189 --> 12:55.984
I don't know what you're talking about.
He's just a friend. He delivers groceries.

12:55.984 --> 12:57.736
- You're so stupid.
- You fucking whore.

12:57.736 --> 12:59.488
- I'm a whore?
- You're invisible.

12:59.488 --> 13:01.281
I'm invisible? Well, I'm not invisible

13:01.281 --> 13:04.243
when I'm looking your micropecker
in its teeny-tiny, little beady eyes.

13:04.243 --> 13:05.661
<i>They drank a lot, and...</i>

13:05.661 --> 13:07.329
What are you looking at?

13:07.329 --> 13:09.831
<i>...I didn't like
spending a lot of time at home.</i>

13:15.420 --> 13:16.588
I'm sorry.

13:18.006 --> 13:20.384
No, I'm sorry.
I should be asking about you.

13:26.515 --> 13:28.767
One sad story is enough for a first date.

13:30.811 --> 13:31.645
I want children.

13:32.896 --> 13:34.022
Excuse me?

13:34.022 --> 13:35.274
I want children. I do.

13:35.274 --> 13:38.151
I want the chance
to be a good husband and a great father.

13:38.151 --> 13:42.155
I think I could do that, you know. I do.
I want a redo.

13:43.866 --> 13:47.202
Maybe we save the wedding planning
until after the movie.

13:47.995 --> 13:50.038
Yeah. Maybe that's a good idea.

14:24.114 --> 14:27.618
Welcome to Lubbick, Weiss and Blackwood.
That's me.

14:29.578 --> 14:31.038
Let me show you to your desk.

14:35.709 --> 14:40.839
<i>It would be accurate to say
that Lillian's first child and only child</i>

14:40.839 --> 14:42.925
<i>was conceived in the beautiful blur</i>

14:43.884 --> 14:45.135
<i>of 1977.</i>

15:02.194 --> 15:05.572
<i>You making yourself a pappy show Melda</i>

15:06.907 --> 15:09.618
<i>You making yourself a bloody clown</i>

15:10.869 --> 15:14.414
<i>Up and down the country looking for Obeah</i>

15:15.249 --> 15:18.544
<i>And your perspiration smell so strong, Well...</i>

15:19.711 --> 15:22.756
<i>Girl, you only wasting time</i>

15:43.986 --> 15:48.866
General Service Unit.
Our car, it's run out of petrol.

15:49.449 --> 15:50.534
Are you carrying any?

15:52.202 --> 15:53.579
Identification.

16:11.305 --> 16:13.891
You, get out. Open the boot.

16:15.225 --> 16:16.602
We can open it from here.

16:22.691 --> 16:24.026
Get out.

16:27.070 --> 16:28.739
I would prefer to stay with my sisters.

16:40.459 --> 16:42.211
Stop it. Hold it. Stop it.

16:43.504 --> 16:44.505
Stop!

16:48.342 --> 16:49.343
Arthur.

16:53.847 --> 16:54.848
Arthur!

17:04.441 --> 17:07.444
Arthur! Arthur! Arthur!

17:10.030 --> 17:13.116
Arthur! Arthur!

17:41.311 --> 17:43.689
I will never let anything happen to you.

17:44.481 --> 17:47.442
I will protect you
with my breath and soul.

17:51.613 --> 17:53.824
Hey, would it be weird
to name a Black kid Rocky?

17:56.869 --> 17:58.829
Wouldn't be weird to name him Apollo.

18:01.039 --> 18:02.040
Apollo.

18:03.208 --> 18:04.209
Yeah.

18:05.961 --> 18:09.715
Hey, you are the god Apollo.

18:12.968 --> 18:15.095
<i>And they lived happily ever after.</i>

18:18.307 --> 18:20.767
<i>Or at least for a few years.</i>

18:21.935 --> 18:27.399
<i>By Apollo's fourth birthday,
Brian West was gone. Vanished.</i>

19:29.086 --> 19:30.087
They're coming.

19:36.844 --> 19:37.845
<i>Bad dream?</i>

19:40.639 --> 19:42.266
It was so strange.

19:43.350 --> 19:48.105
It's this dream that I used to have
all the time when I was little.

19:50.607 --> 19:51.608
About what?

19:53.861 --> 19:54.862
My dad.

19:58.073 --> 19:59.741
My dad, he left when I was four.

20:01.702 --> 20:04.204
But in the dream,
he finally comes back home.

20:06.790 --> 20:08.125
Does he stay?

20:09.626 --> 20:11.044
I never get to that part.

20:14.798 --> 20:16.758
In real life, he never came back.

20:20.721 --> 20:21.722
I'm sorry.

20:33.692 --> 20:34.693
Shit.

20:52.586 --> 20:54.588
"<i>The Sorcerers of Dobu</i>."

21:03.931 --> 21:07.976
Granny and Pops died in each other's arms,
left behind this collection.

21:15.234 --> 21:16.235
Nice books here.

21:17.528 --> 21:19.404
Some of them look good enough to steal.

21:23.492 --> 21:24.660
I'm just kidding.

21:25.494 --> 21:26.578
It's a joke.

21:27.621 --> 21:30.958
I am going to take all of these
for a hundred.

21:33.585 --> 21:34.711
- Deal.
- Deal?

21:35.337 --> 21:37.297
- Yeah.
- Great.

21:42.094 --> 21:43.470
Lubbick, Weiss and Blackwood.

21:43.470 --> 21:44.721
Yes.

22:01.572 --> 22:02.573
Thank you.

22:06.076 --> 22:07.077
Books.

22:28.849 --> 22:29.850
Yes!

22:49.203 --> 22:51.955
Hello, my name is Apollo Kagwa.

22:54.875 --> 22:59.421
Okay. I am the god Apollo.
I am the god Apollo.

23:08.722 --> 23:12.559
